docBody.p:
Several months ago you made me a very pretty and a very welcome Gift, yr excellt Translatn of Titan;
      Jean Paul Richter, Titan: A Romance, trans. Charles T. Brooks, 2 vols. (Boston, 1862).
      —whh surely I ought to have acknowledged sooner: but the truth is, I am frightfully driven abt in these months and years, and have seldom time to write a Note even to friends.

div1.p:
Braid, Betty, b. Pringle (1795–1875), Grace Welsh’s Haddington servant, close to JWC (see 21:82JWC to SS, [29 Oct. 1846],
 and 24:221JWC to TC, [5 Sept. 1849]); b. in Prestonkirk, E. Lothian; m. Alexander (1792–1874), stonemason and shopkeeper. They had one surviving son, George Pringle (1827–65), who suffered ill health. Three other sons d. in infancy: Alexander (b. 1826), James (b. 1829), and James (b. 1831). They had lived at 15 Adam St. (see 17:127TC to JWC, 12 Sept. 1843
) and moved in 1858 to Upper Stenhouse, Liberton, S Edinburgh.
